Hello Chris,
We've been told by Mike R that morphine helps with what's called &quot;Air hunger&quot;,
by some.
(gasping for air)

I was preparing a longer (or different) reply, but after thinking about it all
and a walk, decided that if all his family's there, it's likely they've been
told he could imminently die.
Yes, advanced lung cancer patients sleep a lot; more so during the last few
weeks and then days.
The hearing continues, but may not respond at all times, due to being busy with
coming to terms, the processes going on in his body, hunger, memories, dreams,
hallucinations...the &quot;work of dying&quot;, but if you go, speak to him, close to his
ear. Hold his hand/fingers lightly. There might be a response to your voice,
like a raised eyebrow, opening his eyes, a finger or hand movement.  If so, tell
him what a good friend he's been for you; stay calm, say peaceful things, you'll
see him in a better place where there's no sadness or pain.  If you get choked
up and/or cry too much, excuse yourself and say &quot;I'll be back in a bit&quot;.

It's hard to know what's happening now; whether his family's discussing options
and whether they'll try chemo, or whether he'll be transferred to hospice care
or whether they'll decide to take him home to be with his fur-buddy (dog).
If you decide to go visit, call first, in case he's gone home or passed away.
&lt;or maybe you've received a text message from him&gt;   If he's still there, plan
on staying just a few minutes, then take your cues from the family members as to
how long to stay or whether they want alone time with him or some might want to
speak with you, outside his room (you being a pastor) and if you aren't capable,
without breaking down in tears, I'm sure they'll understand.

I'm sorry I can't help more.
We're just bystanders to what's happening; you and he and the family are on the
front lines.
My thoughts will be with you all.
J
